{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20141118213611|634434643","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Frederica_Wilson","to":"Frederica Wilson"}],"pages":{"13719198":{"pageid":13719198,"ns":0,"title":"Frederica Wilson","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2014-11-18T21:39:30Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Infobox officeholder\n| name=Frederica Wilson\n| image= Frederica Wilson official House portrait.jpg\n| imagesize=\n| state = [[Florida]]\n| district = [[Florida's 24th congressional district|24th]]\n| term_start    = January 3, 2013\n| term_end      =\n| preceded    = [[Sandy Adams]]\n| successor     =  \n| state1 = [[Florida]]\n| district1 = [[Florida's 17th congressional district|17th]]\n| term_start1    = January 3, 2011\n| term_end1      = January 3, 2013\n| preceded1    = [[Kendrick Meek]]\n| successor1    =  [[Tom Rooney (politician)|Tom Rooney]]\n| state_senate2=Florida\n| state2=Florida\n| district2=33rd\n| term_start2=2003\n| term_end2=2010\n| preceded2=[[Kendrick Meek]]\n| succeeded2=[[Oscar Braynon]]\n| state_house3 = Florida\n| district3 = 104th\n| term_start3=1998\n| term_end3=2002\n| preceded3=[[Kendrick Meek]]\n| succeeded3=[[Yolly Roberson]]\n| party=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|birth_name=Frederica Patricia Smith\n| birth_date={{birth date and age|1942|11|05}}\n| birth_place=[[Miami]], [[Florida]]\n| death_date=\n| death_place=\n| alma_mater=[[Fisk University]] <small>([[Bachelor's degree|B.S.]])</small><br/>[[University of Miami]] <small>([[Master's degree|M.S.]])</small>\n| profession=Educator, politician\n| spouse=    {{marriage |Paul Wilson |1963|1988|()=smaller |end=w.}}\n| children=3\n| religion=[[Episcopal Church in the United States of America|Episcopalian]]\n|}}\n\n'''Frederica Patricia Smith Wilson''' (born November 5, 1942) is an [[United States|American]] politician who has been a member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] since 2011. Located in South [[Florida]], Wilson's congressional district&mdash;numbered the [[Florida's 17th congressional district|17th]] during her first two years in Congress, and the [[Florida's 24th congressional district|24th]] since 2013&mdash;is a majority African-American district that includes the southern parts of [[Broward County, Florida|Broward County]] and the eastern parts of [[Miami-Dade County, Florida|Miami-Dade County]]. Included within the district are Pembroke Pines, Hollywood, Miramar, and North Miami. She gained national attention in early 2012 as a result of her high-profile comments on the killing of [[Trayvon Martin]], who was a constituent of hers and whose family she knew personally.{{Citation needed|date=July 2013}}\n\nWilson, who describes herself as a \"voice for the voiceless\", is a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]].<ref name=\"Congressional Bio\">{{cite web|title=MEET CONGRESSWOMAN FREDERICA WILSON|url=http://wilson.house.gov/index.cfm?sectionid=2&sectiontree=2|publisher=Congress|accessdate=24 May 2012}}</ref> Her seat was left open when the incumbent [[Kendrick Meek]] ran for a seat in the Senate in 2010.\n\nWilson is famous for her large and colorful hats, of which she owns several hundred. She has gone through efforts to get Congress to lift its ban on head coverings during House sessions, which dates back to 1837.<ref name = Politifact>{{cite web|title=Congresswoman-elect Frederica Wilson says hat ban started in 1800s but can be waived|url=http://www.politifact.com/florida/statements/2010/nov/19/frederica-wilson/congresswoman-elect-wilson-says-hat-ban-started-18/|work=Politifact|publisher=Politifact|accessdate=23 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Clark|first=Lesley|title=Frederica Wilson backs Nancy Pelosi -- but not the House hat ban|url=http://miamiherald.typepad.com/nakedpolitics/2010/11/frederica-wilson-backs-nancy-pelosi-but-not-the-house-hat-ban.html|publisher=Miami Herald Blog|accessdate=23 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Early life, education, and career ==\nWilson was born '''Frederica Smith''' on November 5, 1942 in [[Miami, Florida]], the daughter of Beulah (n\u00e9e Finley) and Thirlee Smith. Her maternal grandparents were [[Bahamas|Bahamian]].<ref name=bweekly>{{cite news |first=|last=|title=US Congresswoman Frederica Wilson Courtesy calls on Bahamas' Government |url=http://www.thebahamasweekly.com/publish/bis-news-updates/Courtesy_call_on_National_Security_Minister16497.shtml |work=[[Bahamas Weekly]] |publisher= |date=2011-06-20 |accessdate=2011-06-22}}</ref><ref>http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/%7Ebattle/reps/wilsonfrederica.htm</ref> Wilson earned her bachelor of arts degree from [[Fisk University]] in 1963,<ref>http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=W000808</ref> and her master of arts degree from the [[University of Miami]] in 1972.<ref name=\"Frederica S. Wilson FL\">[http://www.votesmart.org/bio.php?can_id=17319 Frederica S. Wilson (FL)], Project Vote Smart</ref> She served as the Principal of Skyway Elementary School in [[Miami]]. She served on the [[Miami-Dade County Public Schools|Miami-Dade County School Board]] from 1992 through 1998.\n\n[[Image:Federicaswilson.jpg|thumb|left|100px|Portrait of State Sen. Wilson in 2007.]]\n\n==Florida Legislature==\nWilson represented District 104 in the [[Florida House of Representatives]] from 1999 to 2002. She then represented the 33rd District in the [[Florida Senate]] from 2003 to 2010. She served as Minority Pro Tempore in 2006, then [[Whip (politics)|Minority Lead Whip]].\n\nAn early supporter, in 2008 she voted for [[Barack Obama]] and [[Joe Biden]] as one of Florida's [[presidential electors]].<ref>[http://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5i5uzTpibgiqcSURUWPVvUQRzYSIQD953FPDO0 AP: It's official: Barack Obama elected 44th president]</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===2010 election===\n{{main|United States House of Representatives elections in Florida, 2010#District 17}}\nWhen [[Kendrick Meek]] retired from [[Florida's 17th congressional district]] to run for the [[United States Senate election in Florida, 2010|United States Senate in 2010]], Wilson ran for the [[Florida's 17th congressional district|open seat]], and won the Democratic nomination to face her Republican challenger to win Meek's seat.<ref>{{cite news | first = Chuck | last = Fadely | title = Frederica Wilson likely headed for 17th district Congressional seat | date = 2010-08-17 | url = http://www.miamiherald.com/508/index.html?media_id=17709643&genre_id=4220 | work = [[Miami Herald]] | accessdate = 2010-09-02 | quote = Frederica Wilson dominated a nine-candidate field for the Democratic nomination for the 17th Congressional seat vacated by Kendrick Meek. With no apparent Republican or Conservative opposition in the general election, she will likely go to Washington. She celebrated Tuesday night at the Chef Creole restaurant in Miami Gardens.}}</ref> On November 2, 2010 she won in the general election without electoral opposition, in a district where the Democratic nomination is [[tantamount to election]].\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|Committee on Foreign Affairs]]'''\n**[[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Asia and the Pacific|Subcommittee on Asia and the Pacific]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Science, Space and Technology|Committee on Science, Space and Technology]]'''\n**[[United States House Science Subcommittee on Space and Aeronautics|Subcommittee on Space and Aeronautics]]\n**[[United States House Science Subcommittee on Technology and Innovation|Subcommittee on Technology and Innovation]]\n\n==Tenure==\n;Education\nWilson's signature issue is education. During her career as an educator, she founded the 5000 Role Models program, which seeks to bring down dropout rates. Since her time in the Florida legislature, she has strongly opposed standardized testing.<ref name=\"Wilson Post\">{{cite news|title=Frederica Wilson (D-Fla.)|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/frederica-wilson-d-fla/gIQA8EKXKP_topic.html#t-a-glance|publisher=Washington Post | date=23 July 2012}}</ref> She has expressed concern with the [[Florida Comprehensive Assessment Test|FCAT]], saying the value of the test is not worth the cost of administering it. She suggested banning the tutoring companies from exploiting vulnerable children, \"even if it means banning companies like Ignite! Learning, founded by ex-Governor [[Jeb Bush]]'s brother, Neil\".<ref name=FCAT>{{cite news|title=FCAT closes door for many students|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2012-04-15/news/fl-wilson-oped0415-20120415_1_fcat-students-graduate-high-school-diploma|newspaper=Sun Sentinel|date=15 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n;Tea Party\nFrederica Wilson has taken a vocal opposition to the [[Tea Party movement|Tea Party]]. At a Miami town hall meeting, she told citizens to remember that the Tea Party is the real enemy and that they hold Congress hostage. She expressed her belief that they have one goal in mind: \"to make President Obama a one-term president.\"<ref name=Enemy>{{cite news|title=Dem Congresswoman: \"The Real Enemy Is The Tea Party\"|url=Dem Congresswoman: \"The Real Enemy Is The Tea Party\"|newspaper=Real Clear Politics|date=23 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n;Trayvon Martin case\nWilson took a vocal stance on the killing of [[Trayvon Martin]], who was a constituent of hers and whose family she says she has known all her life. She has been both praised and criticized for stating shortly after the killing that the motive of the accused, [[George Zimmerman]], was racism. Her most repeated quote was \"Trayvon Was hunted down like a rabid dog. He was shot in the street.\" She called for Zimmerman's arrest \u201cfor his own safety.\u201d<ref name=\"Lawmakers blast\">{{cite news|title=Democratic lawmakers blast police in teen killing|url=http://news.yahoo.com/democratic-lawmakers-blast-police-u-teen-killing-003336954.html|newspaper=Reuters|date=28 March 2012}}</ref> For making this suggestion, she received criticism from conservative quarters. A Breitbart piece noted the only way somebody can be imprisoned for their own safety is if they are a threat to themselves. They cited that the Constitution \"expressly forbids such measures under the Fourth Amendment and the only excuse for a criminal arrest is probable cause.\"<ref name=\"Own Safety\">{{cite web|last=Shapiro|first=Ben|title=DEM CONGRESSWOMAN: ARREST ZIMMERMAN \u2018FOR HIS OWN SAFETY\u2019|url=http://www.breitbart.com/Big-Government/2012/03/28/Democratic-Congresswoman-Arrest-Zimmerman|publisher=Breitbart}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2012, Wilson said \"Justice must be served. No more racial profiling!\"<ref name=\"Calls for Justice\">{{cite news|title=Fla. Rep. Frederica Wilson Calls for Justice on House Floor for Trayvon Martin [Video]|url=http://colorlines.com/archives/2012/03/fla_rep_frederica_wilson_calls_for_justice_on_house_floor_for_trayvon_martin_video.html|newspaper=Color Lines}}</ref> She also went to the House floor and called for the \"murderer\" to be arrested, saying it was an ovious case of racial profiling.<ref name=\"Call for more action\">{{cite news|title=Trayvon Martin shooting spurs lawmakers to call for more action|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503544_162-57401689-503544/trayvon-martin-shooting-spurs-lawmakers-to-call-for-more-action/|newspaper=CBS|date=21 March 2012}}</ref> Wilson organized a rally in Miami on April 1, 2012, calling for Zimmerman's imprisonment. She criticized Florida's self-defense gun law, the so-called Stand Your Ground law, in the wake of Martin's killing, sharing her sentiment that when new laws go on the books, and they work against the people, the laws \"should be looked at and repealed.\"<ref name=\"Nix self-defense law\">{{cite news|last=Dixon|first=Darius|title=Trayvon Martin shooting: Frederica Wilson wants to nix Florida's self-defense gun law|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0312/74301.html|newspaper=Politico|date=21 March 2012}}</ref> In April 2012, Wilson said that the death of Martin was \"definitely\" murder.<ref name=\"Says definitely murder\">{{cite news|title=Trayvon\u2019s death was murder, Congressman Frederica Wilson says|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2012/04/03/2729373/trayvons-death-was-murder-congresswoman.html|newspaper=The Miami Herald|date=4 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nConcern had been raised about Wilson's outspoken comments, with some asking if her rhetoric was \"making it more difficult for the prosecutor to do her job.\"<ref name=\"Martin Transcript\">{{cite news|title=Rhetoric On Trayvon Martin Intensifies Transcript|url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/1203/28/cnr.02.html|newspaper=CNN|date=28 March 2012}}</ref> Wilson has been calling for tougher laws to prevent the racial profiling that led to Martin's death.<ref name=\"Prohibit profiling\">{{cite news|title=Rep. Frederica Wilson calls for tougher laws to prohibit racial profiling|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2012/04/17/2753948/rep-frederica-wilson-calls-for.html|newspaper=The Miami Herald|date=17 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n;Anti-Hazing\n{{further|List of hazing deaths in the United States}}\nWilson led efforts to combat bullying and [[hazing]] both as the South Atlantic Regional Director for [[Alpha Kappa Alpha]] Sorority and as a member of Congress.<ref>http://wilson.house.gov/common/popup/popup.cfm?action=item.print&itemID=189</ref> A Miami Herald reporter nicknamed her \"The Haze Buster\" for her public stance against hazing. She was part of a coalition of African-American fraternity and sorority leaders who launched an anti-Hazing campaign after the 2011 death of Florida A&M drum major [[Robert Champion]] Jr.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2012/05/31/black-groups-launch-anti-hazing-campaign/ | work=Fox News | title=Black groups launch anti-hazing campaign | date=31 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n;Recognition\n\nMSNBC's \u201cThe Grio,\u201d an African-American news and opinion platform, named Wilson a \u201cThe Grio 100\u201d for 2012.<ref name=\"The Grio 2012\">{{cite news|title=The Grio 2012|url=http://video.msnbc.msn.com/the-grio/46397430#46397430|newspaper=MSNBC}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWilson is widowed. She has three children.<ref name=\"Frederica S. Wilson FL\"/> Wilson is an avid wearer of hats. She has a large collection that includes hundreds of hats of all different varieties. She wears one every day to honor her late grandmother. She has asked [[House Speaker]] [[John Boehner]] to waive the rule prohibiting the wearing of hats on the floor of the House of Representatives, a rule in place since 1837.<ref name=Politifact />\n\n== Electoral history ==\n{{Election box begin|title=Democratic Primary 2010<ref>[http://elections.nytimes.com/2010/house/florida/17 Florida 17th District Profile] ''[[The New York Times]]''</ref>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n |party = Democratic Party (US)\n |candidate = Frederica Wilson \n |votes = '''16,653'''\n |percentage = '''35%'''\n |change = }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n|party = Democratic Party (US)\n |candidate = Rudolph Moise\n |votes = 7,769\n |percentage = 16%\n |change = }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n|party = Democratic Party (US)\n |candidate = [[Shirley Gibson]] \n |votes = 5,777\n |percentage = 12%\n |change = }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n|party = Democratic Party (US)\n |candidate = [[Yolly Roberson]] \n |votes = 4,